Docker Hub, and the alternatives.

Docker Hub, at docker dot i-o, is the default registry. When you run docker pull n-ginx, you pull from Hub without naming it. It's free for public images, but it's rate-limited for anonymous pulls, roughly one hundred pulls per address every six hours, since twenty twenty; authenticating or paying raises the cap. That rate limit is the single most common reason teams reach for an alternative, or a cache, which is section nine.

Here are the registries you'll actually meet. GitHub Container Registry, at g-h-c-r dot i-o, is for anything on GitHub; it's free for public images and tightly integrated with GitHub Actions, and it's the common choice for open source. A-w-s e-c-r is for a-w-s workloads, with identity-and-access-management-integrated auth. Google Artifact Registry is for g-c-p workloads. Azure Container Registry is for Azure. Quay is for the Red Hat and OpenShift ecosystem. Harbor is the standard self-hosted option, an on-prem private registry with role-based access control, scanning, and replication. And the plain registry-two image is the o-s-s reference server, for testing or air-gapped networks.

Now, the key point. Because they all speak the same open-container-initiative protocol, you can mix them freely. You might build in continuous integration, push to g-h-c-r for storage, mirror to e-c-r for fast production-side pulls, and run a local cache. The very same docker push and pull commands work against every one of them; only the hostname in the reference changes. So the choice is mostly about where your workloads run, for cloud-native auth, and whether you need self-hosting, with Harbor or registry-two, not about the mechanics, which are identical everywhere.
